Computing the Implied Win Rates¶

We compute the implied probability with the following formula: $$P(x) = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{n=1}^{n} x_n}$$

where $n$ is number of agencies and $x_n$ is the odd (Home/Away/Draw)

Noted that $P(Home) + P(Away) + P(Draw) \neq 1$, this is because of the betting agencies' margin, to adjust, we use the following formula:

$$P(x)_{adjusted} = \frac{P(x)}{P(Home) + P(Away) + P(Draw)}$$

    odds['mean|' + bet] = odds[agent_bet].mean(skipna = True, axis = 1)

    for i in agent_bet:
        odds[i] = odds[i].fillna(odds['mean|' + bet]) # fill na with mean

In [9]:
for agent in agent_list:
    agent_bet = [agent + bet for bet in ["H", "D", "A"]]
    odds[agent + "|implied_home_win_rate"] = odds[agent_bet[0]].apply(lambda x: 1/x)
    odds[agent + "|implied_away_win_rate"] = odds[agent_bet[1]].apply(lambda x: 1/x)
    odds[agent + "|implied_draw_rate"] = odds[agent_bet[2]].apply(lambda x: 1/x)
    odds[agent + "|implied_total"] = odds[agent + "|implied_home_win_rate"] + odds[agent + "|implied_away_win_rate"] + odds[agent + "|implied_draw_rate"]
    
    # adjust the implied win rate
    odds[agent + "|adjusted_implied_home_win_rate"] = odds[agent + "|implied_home_win_rate"] / odds[agent + "|implied_total"]
    odds[agent + "|adjusted_implied_away_win_rate"] = odds[agent + "|implied_away_win_rate"] / odds[agent + "|implied_total"]
    odds[agent + "|adjusted_implied_draw_rate"] = odds[agent + "|implied_draw_rate"] / odds[agent + "|implied_total"]

    
odds["mean|implied_home_win_rate"] = odds["mean|H"].apply(lambda x : 1/x)
odds["mean|implied_away_win_rate"] = odds["mean|A"].apply(lambda x : 1/x)
odds["mean|implied_draw_rate"] = odds["mean|D"].apply(lambda x : 1/x)
odds["mean|implied_total"] = odds["mean|implied_home_win_rate"] + odds["mean|implied_away_win_rate"] + odds["mean|implied_draw_rate"]
    
odds["mean|adjusted_implied_home_win_rate"] = odds["mean|implied_home_win_rate"] / odds["mean|implied_total"]
odds["mean|adjusted_implied_away_win_rate"] = odds["mean|implied_away_win_rate"] / odds["mean|implied_total"]
odds["mean|adjusted_implied_draw_rate"] = odds["mean|implied_draw_rate"] / odds["mean|implied_total"]

Some obsercations here:

  • the implied probability shows that the market is often more confident in the home team
  • people place that bets more certainly when they are confident in the home team
  • people are somehow confused between away or draw when they are not really confident in the home team
  • there is certain threshold for the draw rate

What if we directly use the implied probability model¶

Here we try to use the Monte Carlo method to find how accurate the agencies' implied rates is when comparing to wild guessing

In [17]:
rand_result = match.copy()
In [18]:
repeat = 1000

Random {-1, 0, 1}¶

In [19]:
rand_ls = []
for i in range(repeat):
    rand_result['rand'] = [np.random.randint(low = -1, high = 1) for k in rand_result.index]
    rand_ls.append(metrics.accuracy_score(rand_result['result'], rand_result['rand']))
print("Accuracy Score: " + str(np.array(rand_ls).mean()))

Accuracy Score: 0.2702513430715269

Implied Probability¶

In [22]:
implied_ls = []
for i in range(repeat):
    rand_result['prob'] = rand_result[['mean|adjusted_implied_home_win_rate', 'mean|adjusted_implied_away_win_rate', 'mean|adjusted_implied_draw_rate']].apply(lambda x: np.random.choice([1, -1, 0], p=[x['mean|adjusted_implied_home_win_rate'], x['mean|adjusted_implied_away_win_rate'], x['mean|adjusted_implied_draw_rate']]) , axis = 1)
    rand_ls.append(metrics.accuracy_score(rand_result['result'], rand_result['prob']))
print("Accuracy Score: " + str(np.array(rand_ls).mean()))

Accuracy Score: 0.38199017300833216

Some observations here:

  • directly using the implied probability model in predicting the match results does not really make a lot accurate predictions than wild guessing
  • all of these results are lower than simply betting for home wins

Accuracy Score (Monte Carlo)¶

In [36]:
tree_ls = []
for x in range(repeat):
    clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = 4)
    clf = clf.fit(train_x, train_y)
    predictions = clf.predict(test_x)
    tree_ls.append(metrics.accuracy_score(test_y, predictions))
print("Accuracy Score: " + str(np.array(tree_ls).mean()))

Accuracy Score: 0.5333727985792509

  • but the results are much accurate than wild guessing or simply applying the implied probability
